        "answer": "Audited financial statements are reviewed and verified by an independent certified public accountant (CPA) to ensure they fairly represent the company's financial position in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles (GAAP). They provide a high level of credibility and are often required by regulators, investors, and lenders. Unaudited financial statements, on the other hand, are prepared internally by the company without external verification. While they may still follow GAAP, they lack the assurance of accuracy and reliability provided by an external audit."
