        "answer": "Financial Requirements: State-registered investment advisers must meet certain financial requirements based on their business practices. Advisers who have custody of client funds may be required to maintain a minimum net worth (e.g., $35,000), while those who have discretionary authority but not custody may have a lower threshold (e.g., $10,000).\n\nSubstantial Prepayment of Fees: Advisers who receive substantial prepayment of fees (more than $500 per client and six or more months in advance) must maintain a positive net worth and may be required to provide audited financial statements to clients.\n\nDisclosure of Financial Impairment: Advisers must disclose in Form ADV Part 2 if they have any financial condition that is reasonably likely to impair their ability to meet contractual commitments to clients, such as insolvency or bankruptcy.\n\nFailure to Maintain Minimum Net Worth: If an adviser falls below the required net worth, they must notify the state Administrator by the close of business the next day and file a detailed financial report within a specified period (usually one business day thereafter).\n\nHow to Compute Net Worth: Net worth is calculated as total assets minus total liabilities, but it excludes assets such as goodwill, intangible assets, home furnishings, and personal items not readily marketable. Loans and advances to officers or partners are also excluded from assets."
