        "answer": "Investment Advisers (IAs) are required to fully disclose all actual and potential conflicts of interest to their clients so that clients can make informed decisions. This disclosure must be clear, complete, and in plain language.\n\nConflicts of interest can include:\n\n- Receiving compensation from third parties (such as referral fees or commissions)\n\n- Having financial interests in recommended securities\n\n- Acting in multiple roles, such as adviser and broker or adviser and fiduciary in another capacity\n\n- Managing accounts with differing fee structures that may incentivize the adviser to favor one over another\n\nDisclosure must occur before or at the time of entering into an advisory agreement, typically through Form ADV Part 2A (the brochure). Material changes to conflicts must also be updated promptly and communicated to clients.\n\nFailure to disclose conflicts of interest is considered a fraudulent practice under both federal and state securities laws."
