        "answer": "For client referrals, investment advisers should ensure that any referral arrangements are fully disclosed to the client, including any compensation paid to the solicitor. Written agreements should be in place, and clients must receive a disclosure document outlining the terms of the referral. Advisers must avoid conflicts of interest and ensure that referrals are based on the client’s best interest—not financial incentives alone.\n\nFor trade aggregation and allocation, advisers should aggregate trades when it is likely to result in better overall execution for clients. When allocating aggregated trades, the adviser must ensure fair and equitable distribution across all participating accounts. Allocation must not favor certain clients (such as larger or performance-based accounts) over others. Policies and procedures should be documented and followed consistently, and allocations should be pre-established to prevent favoritism or manipulation."
