        "question": "What are money market funds, and what are their features, restrictions, and risks?",
        "answer": "Money market funds are low-risk mutual funds that invest in short-term, high-quality debt instruments such as Treasury bills, commercial paper, and repurchase agreements.\n\nThey are structured as no-load, open-end investment companies, meaning they do not charge sales loads and investors can redeem shares on demand.\n\nTheir Net Asset Value (NAV) is typically maintained at $1.00 per share, although this is not guaranteed.\n\nKey regulatory restrictions include:\n\n- Investments must be limited to securities with a remaining maturity of no more than 397 days.\n\n- The fund’s average portfolio maturity must not exceed 60 days.\n\n- Securities must have received a rating from a recognized rating agency in the top two short-term categories (or be of comparable quality if unrated).\n\n- Funds must maintain a high level of liquidity to meet redemption requests.\n\nImportant Note: Money market funds are not insured or guaranteed by the FDIC, and it is possible to lose money, although they are designed to be stable and low-risk.\n\nThey are suitable for investors seeking capital preservation and liquidity, such as for emergency savings or short-term goals.",
