        "question": "How does a Traditional IRA work?",
        "answer": "A Traditional IRA (Individual Retirement Account) is a tax-advantaged retirement savings account that allows individuals with earned income to save for retirement.\n\nContributions:\n\n- Individuals can contribute up to the annual IRS limit (with an additional catch-up contribution if age 50 or older).\n\n- Contributions may be fully or partially tax-deductible, depending on income level and participation in an employer-sponsored retirement plan.\n\nTax Treatment:\n\n- Contributions grow tax-deferred, meaning no taxes are paid on investment gains, interest, or dividends while the funds remain in the account.\n- Distributions in retirement are taxed as ordinary income.\n\nWithdrawals:\n\n- Withdrawals can begin without penalty at age 59½.\n\n- Early withdrawals (before 59½) are subject to a 10% penalty and income tax, unless an exception applies (e.g., first-time home purchase, certain medical expenses).\n\n- Required Minimum Distributions (RMDs) must begin by age 73 (or age 72 if born before 1951).\n\nTraditional IRAs are best suited for individuals who expect to be in a lower tax bracket in retirement and want to reduce their taxable income during their working years.",
