        "question": "What is ERISA and what does it regulate?",
        "answer": "The Employee Retirement Income Security Act (ERISA) is a federal law enacted in 1974 that sets minimum standards for retirement and health benefit plans offered by private employers in the United States.\n\nERISA is designed to protect the interests of plan participants and beneficiaries.\n\nKey Provisions:\n\n- Requires plans to provide participants with important information about plan features and funding.\n\n- Establishes fiduciary responsibilities for those managing plan assets. Fiduciaries must act in the best interest of participants with prudence, loyalty, and care.\n\n- Mandates that plans establish a grievance and appeals process for participants to get benefits.\n\n- Gives participants the right to sue for benefits and breaches of fiduciary duty.\n\n- Requires vesting schedules that dictate when employees gain full rights to employer contributions.\n\n- Sets minimum standards for participation, benefit accrual, and funding.\n\nERISA applies to most private-sector employer-sponsored retirement plans, such as 401(k)s, pension plans, and profit-sharing plans. It does not apply to IRAs, government plans, or church plans not electing to be covered.",
