        "answer": "Defined contribution and defined benefit plans are both employer-sponsored retirement plans, but they differ in how benefits are determined and who bears the investment risk.\n\nDefined Contribution Plans:\n\n- The employer, employee, or both make contributions to an individual account for the employee (e.g., 401(k), 403(b), SEP IRA).\n\n- The retirement benefit depends on the total contributions made and investment performance.\n\n- The employee bears the investment risk.\n\n- Benefits are not guaranteed.\n\n- These plans are generally easier to administer and more common in the private sector.\n\nDefined Benefit Plans:\n\n- The employer promises a specific monthly benefit at retirement, usually based on a formula involving salary and years of service.\n\n- The employer bears the investment risk and must ensure the plan is adequately funded.\n\n- Benefits are guaranteed (within limits set by the PBGC—Pension Benefit Guaranty Corporation).\n\n- These plans are more complex and costly to maintain and are less common today, especially in the private sector.",
