        "answer": "**401(k)** and **Roth 401(k)** plans are employer-sponsored retirement savings plans that offer tax advantages and long-term investment growth opportunities.\n\n**401(k):**\n\n- Contributions are made with pre-tax dollars.\n\n- Reduces taxable income in the year of contribution.\n\n- Earnings grow tax-deferred.\n\n- Distributions are taxed as ordinary income.\n\n**Roth 401(k):**\n\n- Contributions are made with after-tax dollars.\n\n- Does not reduce current taxable income.\n\n- Qualified distributions (after age 59½ and held for at least 5 years) are tax-free.\n\n**Benefits of Investing Through a 401(k):**\n\n- High contribution limits ($23,000 in 2024, with $7,500 catch-up for age 50+).\n\n- Employer matching contributions enhance retirement savings.\n\n- Tax-deferred or tax-free growth depending on plan type.\n\n- Automatic payroll deductions promote disciplined saving.\n\n- **Dollar cost averaging** helps reduce the average cost per share over time in a fluctuating market.\n\n- Assets are protected from creditors under federal law.\n\nThese plans are widely used and highly effective tools for retirement planning.",
