        "answer": "SIMPLE (Savings Incentive Match Plan for Employees) IRA plans and SEP (Simplified Employee Pension) IRAs are both employer-sponsored retirement plans designed for small businesses, but they differ in structure, eligibility, and contributions.\n\nSIMPLE IRA:\n\n- Designed for businesses with 100 or fewer employees.\n\n- Employees can make salary deferral contributions (up to $16,000 in 2024, with a $3,500 catch-up for age 50+).\n\n- Employers must either match employee contributions up to 3% of compensation or make a 2% nonelective contribution for all eligible employees.\n\n- Immediate vesting.\n\n- Lower administrative costs than traditional 401(k)s.\n\n- Subject to early withdrawal penalty of 25% if withdrawn within the first 2 years of participation.\n\nSEP IRA:\n\n- Available to businesses of any size, commonly used by sole proprietors and self-employed individuals.\n\n- Only employers can contribute; employees cannot make salary deferrals.\n\n- Contribution limit is up to 25% of compensation or $69,000 in 2024, whichever is less.\n\n- Immediate vesting.\n\n- No annual filing requirement for the employer.\n\nKey Differences:\n\n- SIMPLE IRAs allow employee contributions; SEP IRAs do not.\n\n- SEP IRAs have higher employer contribution limits.\n\n- SIMPLE IRAs require mandatory employer contributions and have withdrawal restrictions within the first 2 years.\n\nBoth are cost-effective options for retirement savings but serve different employer and employee needs.",
