        "question": "What is a Section 457 plan and what are its key features and requirements?",
        "answer": "A Section 457 plan is a nonqualified deferred compensation plan available to employees (and some independent contractors) of state and local governments and certain tax-exempt organizations.\n\nKey Features:\n\n- Section 457 plans are not covered by ERISA, meaning they are not subject to the same nondiscrimination rules that apply to qualified retirement plans like 401(k)s or 403(b)s.\n\n- Because they are nonqualified, these plans may be structured to favor key employees or specific groups.\n\n- Both employees and independent contractors may be eligible to participate in a 457 plan, depending on the sponsoring organization.\n\n- Contribution limits for 2024 are $23,000, with an additional $7,500 catch-up contribution allowed for participants age 50 or older.\n\n- A special catch-up provision allows participants within three years of normal retirement age to contribute up to twice the annual limit, if under-contributed in previous years.\n\nDual Plan Participation:\n\n- It is possible to contribute to both a 457 plan and a 403(b) or 401(k) in the same year, with separate contribution limits applying to each.\n\nLoans:\n\n- Loans from 457(b) plans are permitted only in **governmental** 457 plans—not in nongovernmental 457 plans.\n\nWithdrawals:\n\n- Withdrawals are permitted upon separation from service, death, or due to an unforeseeable emergency.\n\n- Emergency withdrawal standards are stricter than the hardship withdrawal rules under 401(k) plans and must meet the IRS definition of an unforeseeable emergency.\n\nSection 457 plans offer a flexible savings option for public employees and select tax-exempt organizations, often in addition to other retirement accounts.",
