        "answer": "Section 457 plans can be established by either state/local government entities or private tax-exempt organizations, but there are key differences in structure, protections, and rules.\n\nGovernmental 457(b) Plans:\n\n- Offered by state and local government employers (e.g., cities, counties, public schools).\n\n- Must be funded—plan assets must be held in a trust or custodial account for the exclusive benefit of participants.\n\n- Participants have creditor protection because funds are held in trust.\n\n- Loans are permitted, similar to qualified retirement plans.\n\n- Eligible for rollover to other retirement plans such as IRAs, 401(k)s, or 403(b)s.\n\nPrivate (Non-Governmental) 457(b) Plans:\n\n- Offered by private, tax-exempt 501(c)(3) organizations (e.g., hospitals, charities).\n\n- Unfunded and subject to the employer’s general creditors in case of bankruptcy.\n\n- Assets must remain part of the employer’s general assets (not held in a trust for the employee).\n\n- Loans are not permitted.\n\n- Can only be rolled over to another non-governmental 457(b) plan.\n\n- Participation typically limited to a select group of management or highly compensated employees.\n\nIn summary, governmental 457(b) plans offer greater protections and flexibility, while non-governmental 457(b) plans are more restrictive and carry more credit risk.",
