        "question": "What is a SERP (Supplemental Executive Retirement Plan)?",
        "answer": "A Supplemental Executive Retirement Plan (SERP) is a nonqualified deferred compensation plan designed to provide additional retirement income to select key executives.\n\nKey Features:\n\n- SERPs are **nonqualified** plans, meaning they are exempt from ERISA’s nondiscrimination rules and can be offered selectively to executives.\n\n- They are usually funded entirely by the employer as a promise to pay future retirement benefits.\n\n- Because they are nonqualified, SERPs do **not receive preferential tax treatment** like qualified plans.\n\n- Plan benefits are typically **unfunded** and subject to the employer’s general creditors; however, some employers use a **rabbi trust** to informally fund the plan.\n\n- Benefits are taxable to the employee upon distribution, usually at retirement or separation from service.\n\n- SERPs are often used as a retention tool, sometimes with vesting schedules or performance criteria.\n\n- There are no IRS contribution limits, so SERPs allow for larger retirement benefits than qualified plans.\n\nSERPs help employers recruit and retain top talent by offering generous retirement income beyond what qualified plans permit, but they come with credit risk for the employee.",
