        "answer": "When an eligible rollover distribution is made from a qualified retirement plan and is **not** rolled over directly to another qualified plan or IRA, the distribution is subject to **mandatory 20% federal income tax withholding**.\n\nKey points:\n\n- This applies to **lump-sum distributions** made directly to the participant.\n\n- The 20% withholding is required even if the participant plans to complete a **60-day rollover** themselves.\n\n- To avoid withholding, the participant must request a **direct rollover**, where the distribution is sent directly from the plan to another qualified plan or IRA.\n\n- The withholding does **not apply** to required minimum distributions (RMDs), hardship withdrawals, or substantially equal periodic payments.\n\n- If the participant later rolls over the full amount, including the withheld 20%, they must replace it from other funds to defer tax on the full amount.\n\nExample:\nIf $100,000 is distributed to a participant and not rolled over directly, $20,000 will be withheld and only $80,000 received. To roll over the full $100,000 within 60 days, the individual must replace the $20,000 from other sources.",
