        "question": "What are prohibited investments and prohibited transactions under ERISA?",
        "answer": "ERISA prohibits certain investments and transactions to protect plan assets and ensure fiduciaries act solely in the interest of participants and beneficiaries.\n\nProhibited Investments:\n\n- There is no specific list of prohibited investments under ERISA, but all investments must meet the **prudence** and **diversification** standards of Section 404.\n\n- However, investments that are **imprudent**, excessively risky, or result in conflicts of interest are effectively prohibited.\n\n- **Collectibles** (such as artwork, antiques, gems) are generally prohibited in qualified plans, though not explicitly banned under ERISA—rather, they are restricted by the Internal Revenue Code for tax-advantaged accounts.\n\nProhibited Transactions (under Section 406):\n\n- **Self-dealing**: Fiduciaries may not use plan assets for their own benefit.\n\n- **Conflict of interest**: Fiduciaries may not engage in transactions with parties in interest (e.g., employers, service providers, relatives).\n\n- **Transfer of plan assets** to or from a disqualified person.\n\n- **Purchases or sales** of property between the plan and a disqualified person.\n\n- **Loans** to or from the plan to a party in interest.\n\nCertain transactions may be allowed under a **prohibited transaction exemption** (PTE) granted by the Department of Labor (DOL), provided specific conditions are met.\n\nViolations can lead to excise taxes, fiduciary liability, and civil penalties enforced by the DOL or IRS.",
