        "question": "What are the safe harbor provisions of ERISA Section 404(c)?",
        "answer": "ERISA Section 404(c) provides a safe harbor that protects fiduciaries of participant-directed retirement plans (like 401(k) plans) from liability for losses resulting from the participants' own investment decisions, if certain conditions are met.\n\nTo qualify for the 404(c) safe harbor, a plan must:\n\n- Allow participants to exercise control over their accounts by providing a broad range of investment alternatives (at least three core options with materially different risk and return characteristics).\n\n- Permit participants to change investment allocations with a frequency appropriate to the market (generally at least quarterly).\n\n- Provide adequate communication of required information to participants.\n\n- Disclose that the plan intends to comply with Section 404(c) and that fiduciaries may be relieved of liability for losses resulting from participant choices.\n\nIf these requirements are met, fiduciaries are generally not liable for poor investment outcomes resulting from participant decisions.\n\nNote: Fiduciaries are still responsible for selecting and monitoring the plan’s investment options prudently.",
