        "question": "What is a Top-Heavy Plan and what is a Safe Harbor 401(k) Plan?",
        "answer": "A Top-Heavy Plan is a qualified retirement plan where more than 60% of the total account balances or accrued benefits are held by key employees (such as owners and officers).\n\nIf a plan is top-heavy, it must meet special IRS requirements to remain qualified, including:\n\n- Mandatory minimum employer contributions for non-key employees (generally 3% of compensation)\n\n- Faster vesting schedules for all participants\n\nSafe Harbor 401(k) Plans are a type of 401(k) plan that automatically satisfies certain nondiscrimination testing requirements (e.g., ADP and ACP tests) if specific employer contributions and notice requirements are met.\n\nThese plans are not subject to top-heavy rules if they meet safe harbor conditions.\n\nTo qualify as a Safe Harbor 401(k):\n\n- The employer must make one of the following contributions:\n\n  - A matching contribution (e.g., 100% of the first 3% of pay, plus 50% of the next 2%)\n\n  - A non-elective contribution of at least 3% of compensation for all eligible employees\n\n- Contributions must be 100% vested immediately\n\n- An annual notice must be provided to employees detailing their rights and obligations under the plan\n\nSafe Harbor 401(k) Plans help employers avoid complex annual testing while providing predictable benefits to employees.",
