        "question": "What is a Coverdell Education Savings Account (ESA)?",
        "answer": "A Coverdell Education Savings Account (ESA) is a tax-advantaged account used to save for a beneficiary’s qualified education expenses at elementary, secondary, or higher education levels. ESAs are self-directed. \n\nContribution Limitations:\n\n- Total contributions for a single beneficiary cannot exceed $2,000 per year, regardless of the number of contributors\n\n- Contributions are not tax-deductible, and must be made in cash before the beneficiary turns 18 (unless the beneficiary is a special needs individual)\n\nEligibility:\n\n- Contributors must have a modified adjusted gross income (MAGI) below $110,000 for single filers and $220,000 for joint filers (phase-out starts at $95,000 and $190,000, respectively)\n\nQualified Expenses:\n\n- Tuition, fees, books, supplies, equipment, academic tutoring, special needs services, and room and board (if at least half-time)\n\n- Can be used for both K–12 and higher education expenses\n\nTax Treatment:\n\n- Earnings grow tax-free\n\n- Withdrawals are tax-free when used for qualified expenses\n\nAge Limits:\n\n- Contributions must end when the beneficiary turns 18\n\n- Funds must be used or rolled over by age 30 unless the beneficiary has special needs\n\nSpecial Needs Beneficiaries:\n\n- Age restrictions for contributions and distributions do not apply if the beneficiary is considered a special needs individual\n\nRollovers:\n\n- Funds may be rolled over tax-free to another Coverdell ESA for a qualifying family member under age 30 (or any age if special needs)\n\nCoverdell ESAs are flexible tools for education funding and are especially useful for early (K–12) educational expenses.",
