        "question": "What are the two types of Section 529 plans?",
        "answer": "Section 529 plans are tax-advantaged education savings programs established by states to help families save for future education expenses. Unlike ESAs, they are not self-directed. There are two types of 529 plans:\n\n**1. Prepaid Tuition Plans:**\n\n- Allow the purchase of future tuition credits at today’s prices for participating colleges and universities (usually in-state public schools)\n\n- Typically only cover tuition and mandatory fees\n\n- Offer a hedge against tuition inflation but have limited flexibility if the student attends an out-of-state or private institution\n\n- May be backed by the state and come with residency requirements\n\n**2. Education Savings Plans (also called College Savings Plans):**\n\n- Allow individuals to invest contributions in a variety of investment options, such as mutual funds\n\n- Can be used for a broader range of qualified expenses including tuition, fees, room and board, books, and supplies\n\n- Funds can be used at any eligible postsecondary institution in the U.S. and even some abroad\n\n- Withdrawals for qualified expenses are tax-free\n\n- May also be used for up to $10,000 per year in K–12 tuition at private, public, or religious schools\n\nBoth types of 529 plans offer federal tax-free growth and potential state tax benefits depending on the plan and residency.",
