        "question": "How do contributions to a 529 plan work?",
        "answer": "Contributions to a 529 plan are considered completed gifts to the beneficiary for tax purposes, but the **donor retains control** over the account. This means the donor can:\n\nChange the beneficiary\n\nWithdraw the funds (though non-qualified withdrawals may incur income tax and a 10% penalty on earnings)\n\nContributions are made with **after-tax dollars**, and while they are not deductible at the federal level, many states offer state tax deductions or credits.\n\n**Five-Year Gift Tax Averaging:**\n\nA donor can contribute up to 5 times the annual gift tax exclusion amount (currently $18,000 in 2024, or $90,000 total) in a single year per beneficiary and elect to spread the gift evenly over 5 years for gift tax purposes.\n\nIf the donor dies during the 5-year period, a prorated portion of the contribution may be included in the donor's estate.\n\n**Key Points:**\n\nThere is no annual contribution limit, but each state may impose an aggregate maximum (often over $300,000)\n\nThe donor retains control of the assets, including the right to reclaim the funds\n\n529 plan accounts are excluded from the donor’s estate if the donor survives the 5-year period\n\nThis makes 529 plans an effective estate planning and education funding tool.",
