        "question": "How do 529 plans and Coverdell ESAs impact eligibility for need-based financial aid?",
        "answer": "529 plans and Coverdell Education Savings Accounts (ESAs) are considered parental assets if the account owner is a parent. This classification affects how they are treated in the Expected Family Contribution (EFC) calculation on the Free Application for Federal Student Aid (FAFSA).\n\nImpact on Financial Aid:\n\nWhen owned by a parent:\n\n- Counted as a parental asset and assessed at a maximum of 5.64% of the account’s value\n\n- Withdrawals used to pay for qualified education expenses are not treated as income on the FAFSA\n\nWhen owned by a student:\n\n- Treated as a student asset and assessed at up to 20%, reducing eligibility for aid more significantly\n\nWhen owned by a grandparent or other third party:\n\n- Not reported as an asset on the FAFSA\n\n- But, distributions count as untaxed student income the following year and are assessed at up to 50%, which can greatly reduce aid eligibility\n\nPlanning Tip:\n\nTo minimize the impact, grandparent-owned 529 distributions can be delayed until after January 1 of the student’s sophomore year (assuming graduation in four years), as the FAFSA looks at income from two years prior.\n\nIn summary, 529 plans and Coverdell ESAs have a relatively low impact on financial aid if owned by a parent, but can significantly reduce aid if owned by someone else and used for distributions while the student is in school.",
