        "question": "What are the two types of custodial accounts?",
        "answer": "The two types of custodial accounts commonly used to hold assets for minors are the **UGMA** (Uniform Gifts to Minors Act) and **UTMA** (Uniform Transfers to Minors Act).\n\nUGMA (Uniform Gifts to Minors Act):\n\n- Allows financial gifts to a minor in the form of cash, stocks, or mutual funds\n\n- Does not allow for real estate or certain other types of property\n\n- Once gifted, the assets are irrevocable and belong to the minor (indefeasible title)\n\nUTMA (Uniform Transfers to Minors Act):\n\n- Broader than UGMA and allows a wider range of assets, including real estate, patents, and works of art\n\n- Offers more flexibility in the types of gifts that can be transferred\n\n- Also irrevocable and becomes the minor’s property (indefeasible title)\n\nGeneral Rules for Both:\n\n- The account is managed by a custodian (usually a parent or guardian) until the minor reaches the age of majority (usually 18 or 21, depending on the state)\n\n- Once the minor reaches the age of majority, they gain full control of the assets\n\n- The assets in the account are considered the child’s for financial aid purposes and may reduce need-based aid\n\n- Income from the account may be subject to the Kiddie Tax rules\n\nCustodial accounts are not tax-deferred but are useful for gifting and teaching financial responsibility.",
