        "question": "What are the unique features of UTMA accounts compared to UGMA accounts?",
        "answer": "While both UTMA (Uniform Transfers to Minors Act) and UGMA (Uniform Gifts to Minors Act) accounts are custodial accounts used to transfer assets to minors, UTMA offers greater flexibility.\n\n**UTMA Unique Features:**\n\n- Allows a broader range of assets, including real estate, intellectual property, art, and other tangible and intangible assets\n\n- Typically extends the custodianship period beyond age 18 (often to age 21 or even 25, depending on state law)\n\n- Often used when more complex or diverse asset transfers are desired\n\n**UGMA Limitations:**\n\n- Allows only financial assets such as cash, stocks, mutual funds, and bonds\n\n- Custodianship generally ends at the age of majority (usually 18)\n\n- More restrictive in terms of the type of assets that can be gifted\n\n**Shared Characteristics:**\n\n- Irrevocable transfers\n\n- Only one custodian and one minor per account\n\n- Income is reported under the minor’s tax ID\n\n- Funds must be used for the benefit of the minor\n\nIn short, UTMA is more flexible and allows a wider variety of assets and longer custodianship, while UGMA is more limited and may be preferable for simpler gifts of financial assets.",
