        "question": "What is the Kiddie Tax and how does it apply?",
        "answer": "The Kiddie Tax is a tax rule that applies to the unearned income of certain children, to prevent parents from shifting investment income to their lower-taxed children to avoid higher taxes.\n\n**Who It Applies To:**\n\n- Children under age 18\n\n- Children age 18 whose earned income does not exceed half of their support\n\n- Full-time students between ages 19 and 23 whose earned income does not exceed half of their support\n\n**How It Works:**\n\n- The first $1,300 (2024) of a child’s unearned income is tax-free (standard deduction for dependents)\n\n- The next $1,300 is taxed at the child’s rate\n\n- Any unearned income above $2,600 is taxed at the parent’s marginal tax rate\n\n**Types of Unearned Income Affected:**\n\n- Interest\n\n- Dividends\n\n- Capital gains\n\n- Rents and royalties\n\n**Not Affected:**\n\n- Earned income (e.g., wages from a job) is always taxed at the child's rate\n\nThe Kiddie Tax ensures that high-income parents cannot avoid taxes by transferring income-generating assets to their children.",
