        "answer": "Systematic risk is the risk that affects the entire market or a broad segment of the market and cannot be eliminated through diversification. It includes the following key types:\n\n**Market Risk:**\nThe risk of investments declining in value due to overall market movements driven by factors like economic downturns, political events, or global crises.\n\n**Interest Rate Risk:**\nThe risk that changing interest rates will negatively impact investment values, especially bonds. When rates rise, bond prices generally fall.\n\n**Reinvestment Risk:**\nThe risk that proceeds from an investment (e.g., interest or principal repayments) will be reinvested at a lower rate than the original investment.\n\n**Inflation Risk (Purchasing Power Risk):**\nThe risk that inflation will erode the purchasing power of money, reducing the real return on investments.\n\n**Currency (Exchange Rate) Risk:**\nThe risk that fluctuations in foreign exchange rates will affect the value of investments denominated in a foreign currency.\n\nA helpful mnemonic to remember the types of systematic risk is **PRIME**.",
