        "question": "What are stochastic modeling and Monte Carlo simulations, and what are their advantages and disadvantages?",
        "answer": "**Stochastic Modeling**: A type of financial modeling that incorporates randomness and probability distributions to predict a range of possible outcomes. It is used in scenarios where variables are uncertain or volatile (e.g., investment returns, interest rates).\n\n**Monte Carlo Simulation**: A type of stochastic modeling that runs thousands of random trials based on variable assumptions to simulate a wide range of potential outcomes. It is often used in retirement planning and risk analysis.\n\n**Advantages**:\n\n- Provides a more realistic view of uncertainty and variability.\n\n- Useful for stress testing and assessing probabilities of different outcomes.\n\n- Helps in decision-making under uncertainty.\n\n**Disadvantages**:\n\n- Requires strong assumptions and complex input data.\n\n- Results can vary widely depending on model quality and input accuracy.\n\n- Can be computationally intensive and harder to interpret without proper context."
