        "question": "What is the Capital Asset Pricing Model (CAPM)?",
        "answer": "The **Capital Asset Pricing Model (CAPM)** is a formula used to determine the expected return of an investment based on its systematic risk (beta).\n\nIt helps investors evaluate whether a security is fairly valued given its risk relative to the overall market.\n\nThe basic premise is that every investment carries two types of risk:\n\n- **Systematic Risk**: Market-wide risk that cannot be diversified away (e.g., interest rates, inflation, recessions).\n\n- **Unsystematic Risk**: Asset-specific risk that can be reduced or eliminated through diversification.\n\n**CAPM Formula**:\n\nExpected Return = Risk-Free Rate + Beta × (Market Return – Risk-Free Rate)\n\n**Key Components**:\n\n- **Risk-Free Rate**: The return on a riskless investment (e.g., Treasury bills).\n\n- **Beta**: Measures the asset’s volatility compared to the market.\n\n- **Market Risk Premium**: The additional return expected from the market over the risk-free rate.\n\n**Assumptions**:\n\n- Markets are efficient\n\n- Investors are rational and risk-averse\n\n- Returns are normally distributed\n\nCAPM is widely used in portfolio management and corporate finance to estimate the cost of equity.\n\n"
