        "id": 447,
        "question": "What are mutual fund returns, holding period returns, and annualized returns, and what are their formulas?",
        "answer": "**Mutual Fund Return**:\n\nMeasures the percentage gain or loss of a mutual fund over a specific time period, including dividends and capital gains distributions.\n\n**Formula**:\n\nMutual Fund Return = (Ending NAV – Beginning NAV + Distributions) ÷ Beginning NAV\n\n\n**Holding Period Return (HPR)**:\n\nRepresents the total return earned during the entire period an investment is held, regardless of length.\n\n**Formula**:\n\nHPR = (Ending Value – Beginning Value + Income Received) ÷ Beginning Value\n\n\n**Annualized Return**:\n\nConverts a total return over a holding period into an average annual return to allow comparisons between investments held for different time frames.\n\n**Formula**:\n\nAnnualized Return = (1 + HPR)^(1/n) – 1\n\nWhere **n** = number of years the investment was held.\n\nAnnualized return smooths out returns and assumes compounding.\n\n"
