        "question": "What is Internal Rate of Return (IRR)?",
        "answer": "**Internal Rate of Return (IRR)** is the discount rate that makes the net present value (NPV) of all future cash flows from an investment equal to zero.\n\nIt is the rate at which an investment breaks even in present value terms and is commonly used to evaluate profitability over time.\n\nIRR is the **preferred method of measuring the return on a Direct Participation Program (DPP)** because it accounts for irregular and long-term cash flows.\n\nIRR **takes into consideration the time value of money**, meaning it recognizes that money received today is worth more than the same amount received in the future.\n\nIRR is also the method used to **calculate the Yield to Maturity (YTM) of a bond**, as it equates the bond's current price with the present value of its future interest payments and principal.\n\n"
