        "question": "What are cash accounts and which accounts must be cash accounts?",
        "answer": "**Cash Accounts**:\n\nA cash account is a brokerage account in which the investor must pay the full amount for securities purchased by the settlement date. No borrowing or margin is allowed.\n\nInvestors can only trade with the actual cash available in the account.\n\nCash accounts are the most basic type of brokerage account and are often used by conservative investors or those who are restricted from using margin.\n\n\n**Accounts That Must Be Cash Accounts**:\n\n- **Custodial Accounts** (UGMA/UTMA): Must be cash accounts because minors cannot legally enter into margin agreements.\n\n- **Retirement Accounts** (e.g., IRAs, 401(k)s) and other tax-advantaged accounts: Must be cash accounts; margin trading is prohibited under IRS rules.\n\n- **Corporate or Trust Accounts** (unless specifically approved for margin): Often default to cash accounts unless explicit margin authorization is granted.\n\nThese rules help protect investors and account holders from the risks associated with borrowing.\n\n"
