        "answer": "**Market Order**:\n\nAn order to buy or sell a security immediately at the best available current price. It guarantees execution but not the price.\n\n\n**Limit Order**:\n\nAn order to buy or sell a security at a specific price or better. A buy limit is executed at the limit price or lower; a sell limit is executed at the limit price or higher. It does not guarantee execution.\n\n\n**Stop Order (Stop-Loss Order)**:\n\nAn order that becomes a market order once a specific stop price is reached. It’s used to limit losses or protect profits.\n\n- Example: A stop-sell order at $45 becomes a market order to sell once the stock trades at or below $45.\n\n\n**Stop-Limit Order**:\n\nSimilar to a stop order, but once the stop price is reached, it becomes a **limit** order instead of a market order. It requires both a stop price and a limit price.\n\nExecution is not guaranteed if the market moves past the limit.\n\n\n**Day Order**:\n\nValid only for the trading day it is placed. If not executed by market close, it is automatically canceled.\n\n\n**Good-’Til-Canceled (GTC) Order**:\n\nRemains active until it is executed or canceled by the investor. Most brokerages automatically cancel GTC orders after a set period (e.g., 30 or 90 days).\n\n"
